(i) A ∆ B
The symmetric difference of two sets A and B, denoted as A ∆ B, is the set of elements which are in either of the sets, but not in their intersection. In other words, A ∆ B = (A ∪ B) - (A ∩ B).

A = {1, 2, 3}
B = {2, 3, 4}
A ∪ B = {1, 2, 3, 4}
A ∩ B = {2, 3}

A ∆ B = {1, 4}

(ii) A' ∆ B'
To find the complements of A and B, we need to know the universal set U. Since it is not given, let's assume U contains all the elements in A and B.

U = {1, 2, 3, 4}

A' = U - A = {4}
B' = U - B = {1}

A' ∆ B' = (A' ∪ B') - (A' ∩ B') = ({1, 4}) - {} = {1, 4}

(iii) (A ∆ B)' and A' ∆ B'

(A ∆ B)' = U - (A ∆ B) = {1, 2, 3, 4} - {1, 4} = {2, 3}

Now, we compare (A ∆ B)' and A' ∆ B':

(A ∆ B)' = {2, 3}
A' ∆ B' = {1, 4}

Since (A ∆ B)' ≠ A' ∆ B', we can conclude that the symmetric difference of two sets is not distributive over complement.
